result.execSummary:
On one or more charges, the deferred prosecution or sentencing agreement(s) on this case were fulfilled, and the charge(s) were dismissed.

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

Defendant Tabitha A. Kieliszewski in court with attorney Acalia N Halverson. David R. Knaapen appeared for the State of Wisconsin.
Cases heard at this time are 16CM-4 and 16CM-261.

8:52 AM Court calls cases.
Court apologizes to parties for being tardy.

Court states appearances.

Matters are set for a plea today.

Atty Knaapen states that in 16CM-4, Defendant will plead to Count 1. Count 2 and 3 would be dismissed and read in.
In 16CM-261, Defendant will plead to Count 1. Count 2 would be dismissed and read in.

Atty Halverson concurs.

Plea questionnaire/Agreement filed.

Defendant enters a plea of: NO CONTEST 16CM-4 Count 1.
Defendant enters a plea of: NO CONTEST 16CM-261 Count 1.

Court questions Defendant regarding pleas.
Court informs Defendant of Constitutional Rights. Court advises Defendant of Elements State must prove for the Charge.
Court questions AttorneyHalverson for Defendant.
Court finds Defendant's Plea is freely, voluntarily and intelligently made.
Attorneys stipulate that there is factual basis for the charges.
State has complied with victim notification statutes.

BY THE COURT:
Court finds a sufficient factual basis to support the charges.
Court finds the defendant guilty.  Clerk directed to WITHOLD entry Judgment of Conviction this date.
16CM-4: Count 1: Contrary to the statute section stated therein
16CM-4: Count 2: Dismissed and read in
16CM-4: Count 3: Dismissed and read in
16CM-261: Count 1: Contrary to the statute section stated therein
16CM-261: Count 2: Dismissed and read in

Atty Knaapen makes sentencing arguments to the Court, addresses restitution. 
Atty Halverson makes sentencing arguments to the Court, this is a joint recommendation.

Address is verified.

BY THE COURT:
16CM-4:
Count 1:
Sentence is Withheld
VIP Program for  a period of 9 Months
Conditions:
Pay $33.39 to Walmart within 30 days
Perform 25 hours of community service
Complete a 4 hour online shoplifting prevention class
Participate in other community based services as recommended by the director
If Defendant successfully completes the program, 16CM-4 would be dismissed

16CM-261:
Count 1:
Sentence is Withheld
VIP Program for a period of 9 Months, concurrent to 16CM-4
Conditions:
Comply with conditions as stated in 16CM-4
If Defendant successfully comples the program, State would move to amend this to an ordinance violation - $50 fine plus costs

If Defendant is not successful, Defendant will be back in Court for sentencing.
